Actually, simply setting the `delimiter` to `'#'` or the `delimiterString` to `"#"` results in the exception.

```java
@ParameterizedTest
@CsvSource(value = "test", delimiter = '#')
void test(String str) {
}
```

This naturally applies to `@CsvFileSource` as well, and I have updated this issue's title to reflect that.

@hwellmann, thanks for your bug report! 

As @sbrannen noted, the code you shared indeed throws an exception in JUnit 6, whereas it worked as expected in JUnit 5.

There reason of such behavior is quite straightforward: JUnit previously relied on [univocity-parsers](https://github.com/uniVocity/univocity-parsers) while working with CSV data, but JUnit 6 [has migrated](https://github.com/junit-team/junit-framework/issues/4339) to [FastCSV](https://fastcsv.org/).

These two libraries provide a similar set of features, however, they have subtle differences in behavior. The case you've found is exactly one of such differences.

-------

First of all, both libraries use `#` as the default "comment character". That said, while _univocity-parsers_ allows to use the same character as both "comment character" and "delimiter", _FastCSV_ prohibits this and explicitly requires to specify "different control characters".

To fix this, _different characters must be used for comments and delimiters_.

As of `6.0.0` the only way to achieve this is to replace `delimiterString = "#"` with another character, for example `delimiterString = "|"`.
However, this also requires to change test data which might not be an option. 

That's why it may be useful to introduce an explicit way to configure "comment character":
```java
@ParameterizedTest
@CsvSource(delimiterString = "#", commentCharacter = ";" textBlock = """
    foo # bar
    """)
void csv(String a, String b) {
}
```
With this change, the only adjustment required from a user, would be to explicitly declare `commentCharacter` in the `@Csv{File}Source` annotations, without changing the configured delimiters.

A draft PR is available here: https://github.com/junit-team/junit-framework/pull/5031

@hwellmann, please, let me know if any of the proposed options would work for your case.
@marcphilipp @sbrannen @osiegmar WDYT?
